hands_on_practices.solution:
1. At steady state, the upward transition rate equals the downward rate:  
$$n_1B_{12}u'_\nu \;=\; n_2\Bigl(A_{21}+B_{21}u'_\nu\Bigr)\,. $$  
2. Hence  
$$\frac{n_2}{n_1}
=\frac{B_{12}u'_\nu}{A_{21}+B_{21}u'_\nu}\,. $$  
3. Use $g_1B_{12}=g_2B_{21}$, $A_{21}/B_{21}=8\pi h\nu^3/c^3$, and $u'_\nu=W u_\nu(T)$. The ratio can be expressed as:
$$\frac{n_2}{n_1}
=\frac{\frac{g_2}{g_1}B_{21}u'_\nu}{B_{21}\bigl(\tfrac{A_{21}}{B_{21}}+u'_\nu\bigr)}
=\frac{g_2}{g_1}\frac{u'_\nu}{\frac{8\pi h\nu^3}{c^3}+u'_\nu}
=\frac{g_2}{g_1} \frac{1}{\frac{1}{W}\left(e^{h\nu/k_BT}-1\right)+1}\,. $$
4. Simplify the denominator:  
$$\frac{n_2}{n_1}
=\frac{g_2}{g_1} \frac{W}{e^{h\nu/k_BT}-1+W} = \frac{g_2W}{g_1\bigl(e^{h\nu/k_BT}+W-1\bigr)}\,. $$  
5. The excited‐state fraction is  
$$f_2=\frac{n_2}{n_1+n_2}
=\frac{\frac{n_2}{n_1}}{1+\frac{n_2}{n_1}}
=\frac{g_2W}{g_1\bigl(e^{h\nu/k_BT}+W-1\bigr)+g_2W}\,. $$
